Successfully configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project.

## What was implemented:

1. **Fetched latest documentation**: Retrieved the most up-to-date installation instructions from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart

2. **Verified existing package**: The `@vercel/analytics` package (v1.6.1) was already installed in package.json

3. **Added Analytics component**: Added the `<Analytics />` component to the root layout file following the official Next.js App Router instructions

## Files modified:

- **src/app/layout.tsx**: 
  - The Analytics import was already present: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next"`
  - Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the `<Footer />` component
  - This placement follows Vercel's recommendation to add Analytics after the main content

## Implementation details:

- This is a Next.js App Router project (identified by the `src/app/layout.tsx` structure)
- Following the official documentation, the Analytics component was added to the root layout
- No environment variables or additional configuration are required
- The Analytics component will automatically track page views when the site is deployed to Vercel

## Verification:

- ✅ Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
- ✅ TypeScript compilation passed without errors
- ✅ All 7 routes generated correctly in production build
- ✅ No linting errors (project doesn't have linting configured)

## Next steps:

To enable Web Analytics:
1. Deploy this change to Vercel using `vercel deploy`
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard under the Analytics tab
3. After deployment, verify installation by checking the browser's Network tab for requests to a path like `/<unique-path>/view`

The Analytics component is now properly configured and will begin tracking once deployed to Vercel.
